Approach 1: Doubly Linked List
class Node {
    Node prev;
    Node next;
    String data;
    
    Node(String data) {
        this.data = data;
        prev = next = null;
    }
}

class BrowserHistory {
    Node curr;

    public BrowserHistory(String homepage) {
        curr = new Node(homepage);
    }
    
    public void visit(String url) {
        Node newNode = new Node(url);
        curr.next = newNode;
        newNode.prev = curr;
        curr = newNode; // Move current pointer to the newly visited page
        // Any old forward history is automatically cut off and garbage collected!
    }
    
    public String back(int steps) {
        // Move back until we hit the beginning of history OR run out of steps
        while (steps > 0 && curr.prev != null) {
            curr = curr.prev;
            steps--;
        }
        return curr.data;
    }
    
    public String forward(int steps) {
        // Move forward until we hit the end of history OR run out of steps
        while (steps > 0 && curr.next != null) {
            curr = curr.next;
            steps--;
        }
        return curr.data;
    }
}


Approach 2: ArrayList
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

class BrowserHistory {
    private List<String> history;
    private int currIndex;
    private int maxIndex;

    public BrowserHistory(String homepage) {
        history = new ArrayList<>();
        history.add(homepage);
        currIndex = 0;
        maxIndex = 0;
    }
    
    public void visit(String url) {
        currIndex++;
        // If we are overwriting existing forward history, update the element
        if (currIndex < history.size()) {
            history.set(currIndex, url);
        } else {
            history.add(url);
        }
        // Move the boundary marker to the current position, clearing forward history
        maxIndex = currIndex;
    }
    
    public String back(int steps) {
        // Ensure we don't go past the homepage (index 0)
        currIndex = Math.max(0, currIndex - steps);
        return history.get(currIndex);
    }
    
    public String forward(int steps) {
        // Ensure we don't go past the newest available history (maxIndex)
        currIndex = Math.min(maxIndex, currIndex + steps);
        return history.get(currIndex);
    }
}


# 1. Time Complexity: A Hidden Win for Array

On paper, both approaches look identical in terms of asymptotic time complexity:

- **visit:** `O(1)` for both.
- **back / forward:** `O(steps)` for the Linked List, and technically `O(1)` arithmetic for the Array.  
  However, because the problem limits the number of steps or requires returning the element, the absolute time bounds are similar.

**The Real Difference:**  
The Array approach performs the boundary check instantly using basic math (`O(1)`), whereas the Linked List requires a `while` loop to physically traverse nodes one by one. In practice, jumping directly to an index is much faster than pointer chasing.

---

# 2. Memory Efficiency (Cache Locality)

- **Doubly Linked List:** Each page visit allocates a brand new Node object on the heap. Each node stores a `String` reference and two pointer references (`prev` and `next`). These nodes are scattered across memory, which causes cache misses when traversing back and forth.
- **Array/ArrayList:** Elements are stored in contiguous memory blocks. More importantly, when you go back and visit a new page, the Array overwrites the existing index instead of throwing it away. It reuses the memory, significantly reducing garbage collection overhead.

---

# 3. Code Maintainability and Safety

- **Doubly Linked List:** Managing pointers manually is highly prone to edge‑case bugs. A single misplaced pointer can easily lead to a `NullPointerException` (as seen in your original error).
- **Array/ArrayList:** The logic relies entirely on simple index boundaries (`currIndex` and `maxIndex`). There are no pointers to manage, making the code clean, readable, and virtually impossible to throw a `NullPointerException`.

---

# Quick Comparison Table

| Feature              | Doubly Linked List                  | Array / ArrayList (Best)       |
|----------------------|-------------------------------------|--------------------------------|
| **visit Time**       | O(1)                                | O(1)                           |
| **back/forward Time**| O(steps)                            | O(1)                           |
| **Memory Overhead**  | High (3 references per node)        | Low (Contiguous array layout)  |
| **Memory Reuse**     | No (Deletes forward history)        | Yes (Overwrites forward history)|
| **Code Simplicity**  | Complex (Pointer management)        | Simple (Index arithmetic)      |


